<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-275-174  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 275 174.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 27 1989 v3 n9 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Panel pushes for central DOD procurement body. (Department ofDefense)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reed, Fred.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A congressional panel sponsored by the Military Reform Caucusconcludes that the current system of procurement is too flawed tobe fixed.andP;  The panel, co-chaired by Sen.andP;  William Roth andincluding former Pentagon procurement expert Richard Godwin andRep Barbara Boxer, states that the US needs a central civilianagency, insulated from outside influence to manage weaponsprocurement.andP;  Boxer presented a summary of her HR 965 bill at thediscussion, which would establish a central buying agency.andO;Provisions of the bill include establishing a civilian independentprocurement corps to procure all property and services for theDOD, using highly trained professionals in acquisitions-relatedfields who would be the sole negotiators for the contract, andclosing the revolving door between industry and the military,using instead an independent inspector general to audit the corp'sactivities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Defense ContractsUnited States. Department of DefenseUpgradingGuidelinesCritiquePurchasing Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>